          "title": "The lament as sustained accusation (vv. 9-16)",
          "body": "The pivot at verse 9 is one of the most jarring in the Psalter: 'Yet You have rejected us and brought us to dishonor, and do not go out with our armies.' The grammar is second-person throughout — the community does not say 'we are defeated' but 'You have rejected,' 'You cause us to turn back,' 'You give us as sheep,' 'You sell Your people,' 'You make us a reproach.' Every predicate is divine action. The psalmist refuses the comforting alternative that God is merely absent; the claim is that God is actively responsible. The specificity of the humiliation is relentless: plundering (44:10), slaughter and scattering (44:11), cheapness without profit (44:12), reproach from neighbors (44:13), international byword and laughingstock (44:14), unceasing personal shame before the scorner and avenger (44:15-16). The commercial language of verse 12 — 'You sell Your people cheaply, and have not profited by their sale' — is deliberately provocative. It accuses God not of cruelty but of carelessness, as if Israel were sold at a loss. This is hyperbolic rhetoric of grief, not systematic theology, but Scripture canonizes it as a legitimate form of address. The community is not sinning by speaking this way; it is praying."
