          "title": "The petition — bold address to the God who seems asleep (vv. 23-26)",
          "body": "The psalm's final four verses contain three imperatives directed at God: 'Arouse Yourself' (44:23), 'Awake' (44:23), 'Rise up' (44:26). The anthropomorphism of a sleeping God is startling, but it is canonical — the psalmist is not asserting that God is literally unconscious but employing the most viscerally evocative language available for experienced divine absence. Elijah uses the same image sarcastically against Baal (1 Kings 18:27); the psalms use it earnestly against Yahweh (Psalm 7:6; 35:23; 59:4). The difference is everything — mockery and prayer inhabit the same grammar, but their orientations are opposite. The petition 'do not reject us forever' (44:23) concedes the reality of the rejection while appealing for its limitation. 'Why do You hide Your face and forget our affliction and our oppression?' (44:24) reprises the face-theology of verse 3 — the same face that once shone with favor now seems turned away. The posture of verse 25 — 'our soul has sunk down into the dust; our body cleaves to the earth' — is prostration both physical and spiritual, the lowest point in the psalm. Out of that prostration rises the final petition: 'Rise up, be our help, and redeem us for the sake of Your lovingkindness' (44:26). The word *chesed* — lovingkindness, covenant faithful love — is the psalm's last word and only remaining argument. After memory, complaint, and protest have been exhausted, the community has nothing left to offer but the character of God Himself. This is the psalm's profound wisdom: when you have no explanation, no resolution, and no remaining leverage, *chesed* is enough to pray."
